##DTI by credit score

Ideally, DTI should align with Credit Score (High Score = Low DTI). If someone has a high DTI and high transaction volume, they are very risky because they are spending heavily while already being deep in debt—a recipe for default!

df_merged['credit_score'].value_counts()

df_merged.info()

df_merged1 = df_merged.drop(columns=['per_capita_income', 'cvv', 'acct_open_date', 'card_number'])

df_merged1.info()

# Categorizing Credit Scores
bins = [300, 579, 669, 739, 799, 850]  # Define intervals for credit scores
labels = ['Poor', 'Fair', 'Good', 'Very Good', 'Exceptional']  # Define categories
df_merged1['score_category'] = pd.cut(df_merged1['credit_score'], bins=bins, labels=labels)

# Grouping the data by score category to calculate averages
score_analysis = df_merged1.groupby('score_category', observed=False).agg({
# score_analysis = df_merged1.groupby('score_category').agg({
    'DTI': 'mean',
    'count_nonfraud_trx_L6M': 'mean',
    'amt_nonfraud_trx_L6M': 'mean'
}).reset_index()

print(score_analysis)

1. "Poor" Category (The High-Risk Spenders)
Users with Poor credit scores are actually the biggest spenders (187M total amount) and the most frequent users (250 transactions). Because their score is already "Poor," the bank is at a very high risk of not getting this 187M back.

2. Fair Category (Struggle Spenders)
The Fair category has the highest DTI (0.29). They have the highest debt to income. DTI went up (from 0.22 in Poor to 0.29 in Fair) but their spending dropped (from 187M to 145M). This suggests potential financial stress.

3. Good Category (Stable)
As credit scores improve, transaction counts decline (with the "Good" categories showing lower transaction amounts and counts).

4. The Very Good & Exceptional (Safe)
The Observation: These groups have the lowest DTI (0.21) and the most stable, conservative spending (around 114M–115M).

