Positive Correlation :
The general trend suggests a positive correlation between income and credit limit. As income increases, the credit limit tends to increase as well. This alignment indicates that clients with higher incomes are often deemed lower risk by lenders and therefore are offered higher credit limits.

Outliers :
A few points at the upper right of the chart reflect clients with very high incomes (over 3 million) and correspondingly high credit limits (up to 2 million). These could be potential "high rollers" who may have significant financial responsibility and credit history, making them attractive to banks for lending.

